This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Absolute Sobriety from all alcohol and drugs. If a prescription is received the DE must maintain it in it's original bottle showing the DE's name, the name of the substance and the name of the doctor who prescribed it.

3:25 PM Defendant Jaime L. Cornwell appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Annie E Getsinger appeared by video for Jaime L. Cornwell.  Prosecuting attorney C. Remington McConnell in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Court states case and appearances.  Defendant received and waives reading of complaint.  Court advises DE of charges/max penalties.  Court finds probable cause.  DE doesn't qualify for PD appt.  Advised of rights to an attorney.  State makes bail argument.  Atty Getsinger responds.  Time limits waived for preliminary hearing.  $500.00 signature bond set.  Special bond conditions as follows:  Absolute sobriety from all alcohol and drugs. If a prescription is received the DE must maintain it in it's original bottle showing the DE's name, the name of the substance and the name of the doctor who prescribed it.
